msgctxt "mn106:0.1"
msgid "Majjhima Nikāya 106 "
msgstr "Middle Discourses 106 "

#. HTML: </p><h1>
msgctxt "mn106:0.2"
msgid "Āneñjasappāyasutta "
msgstr "Conducive to the Imperturbable "

#. HTML: </h1></div><p><span class="evam">
#. REF: nya1, sc1
msgctxt "mn106:1.1"
msgid "Evaṃ me sutaṃ—"
msgstr "So I have heard. "

#. HTML: </span>
msgctxt "mn106:1.2"
msgid "ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kurūsu viharati kammāsadhammaṃ nāma kurūnaṃ nigamo. "
msgstr "At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Kurus, near the Kuru town named Kammāsadamma. "

msgctxt "mn106:1.3"
msgid "Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi: "
msgstr "There the Buddha addressed the mendicants, "

msgctxt "mn106:1.4"
msgid "“bhikkhavo”ti. "
msgstr "“Mendicants!” "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "mn106:1.5"
msgid "“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ. "
msgstr "“Venerable sir,” they replied. "

msgctxt "mn106:1.6"
msgid "Bhagavā etadavoca: "
msgstr "The Buddha said this: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: nya2, pts-vp-pli2.262, sc2
msgctxt "mn106:2.1"
msgid "“Aniccā, bhikkhave, kāmā tucchā musā mosadhammā. "
msgstr "“Mendicants, sensual pleasures are impermanent, hollow, false, and deceptive, "

# NOTE: balalapana is found at Thig 5.2 of a beautiful body, and at SN 22.95 we have balalapini, where BB has “beguiler of fools” noting that the comm says this refers to vinnana, although this doesn’t seem completely certain. At Ja 421 we have of kama: Ahahā bālalapanā, “Oh, oh, the cries of fools.” I think this context gives a good idea, it means something like “cooed over by fools”, or in the case of lapini, clumsily: “causing fools to coo over it.”
msgctxt "mn106:2.2"
msgid "Māyākatametaṃ, bhikkhave, bālalāpanaṃ. "
msgstr "made by illusion, cooed over by fools. "

msgctxt "mn106:2.3"
msgid "Ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā; "
msgstr "Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come, "

msgctxt "mn106:2.4"
msgid "yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā—"
msgstr "sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come; "

#. VAR: mārassesa → mārasseva (mr)
msgctxt "mn106:2.5"
msgid "ubhayametaṃ māradheyyaṃ, mārassesa visayo, mārassesa nivāpo, mārassesa gocaro. "
msgstr "both of these are Māra’s sovereignty, Māra’s domain, and Māra’s territory. "

msgctxt "mn106:2.6"
msgid "Etthete pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi saṃvattanti. "
msgstr "They conduce to bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression. "

msgctxt "mn106:2.7"
msgid "Teva ariyasāvakassa idhamanusikkhato antarāyāya sambhavanti. "
msgstr "And they create an obstacle for a noble disciple training here. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: nya3
msgctxt "mn106:3.1"
msgid "Tatra, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati: "
msgstr "A noble disciple reflects on this: "

msgctxt "mn106:3.2"
msgid "‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā; "
msgstr "‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come, "

msgctxt "mn106:3.3"
msgid "yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā—"
msgstr "sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come; "

msgctxt "mn106:3.4"
msgid "ubhayametaṃ māradheyyaṃ, mārassesa visayo, mārassesa nivāpo, mārassesa gocaro. "
msgstr "both of these are Māra’s sovereignty, Māra’s domain, and Māra’s territory. "

msgctxt "mn106:3.5"
msgid "Etthete pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi saṃvattanti, "
msgstr "They conduce to bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression. "

msgctxt "mn106:3.6"
msgid "teva ariyasāvakassa idhamanusikkhato antarāyāya sambhavanti. "
msgstr "And they create an obstacle for a noble disciple training here. "

msgctxt "mn106:3.7"
msgid "Yannūnāhaṃ vipulena mahaggatena cetasā vihareyyaṃ abhibhuyya lokaṃ adhiṭṭhāya manasā. "
msgstr "Why don’t I meditate with an abundant, expansive heart, having mastered the world and stabilized the mind? "

msgctxt "mn106:3.8"
msgid "Vipulena hi me mahaggatena cetasā viharato abhibhuyya lokaṃ adhiṭṭhāya manasā ye pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi te na bhavissanti. "
msgstr "Then I will have no more bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression. "

msgctxt "mn106:3.9"
msgid "Tesaṃ pahānā aparittañca me cittaṃ bhavissati appamāṇaṃ subhāvitan’ti. "
msgstr "And by giving them up my mind, no longer limited, will become limitless and well developed.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "mn106:3.10"
msgid "Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati. "
msgstr "Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension. "

# NOTE: MS punctuation is incorrect. The idioms here are odd. The comm gives an extensive and implausible explanation, which begins by proposing that the sequence of the text be reversed! Etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati. Paññāya vā adhimuccatīti ettha etarahi vā paññāya adhimuccati, āneñjaṃ vā samāpajjatīti evaṃ padaparivattanaṃ katvā attho veditabbo. The Chinese at MA 75 has 以慧為解 “liberated by wisdom”, which is surely a more persuasive reading. I suggest there was an old corruption from vimuccati to adhimuccati. See https://discourse.suttacentral.net/t/free-or-confident/2806
#. VAR: āneñjaṃ → ānejjaṃ (si) | āṇañjaṃ (pts1)
msgctxt "mn106:3.11"
msgid "Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā. "
msgstr "Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom. "

# NOTE: Unfortunately, samvattanika doesn’t really mean “evolving”. The normal meaning of samvattanika is “leading on, conducive to”, and the point here is that the state of consciousness developed in meditation is conducive to such a rebirth.
msgctxt "mn106:3.12"
msgid "Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ. "
msgstr "When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable. "

msgctxt "mn106:3.13"
msgid "Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati. "
msgstr "This is said to be the first way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: nya4, sc3
msgctxt "mn106:4.1"
msgid "Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati: "
msgstr "Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects: "

msgctxt "mn106:4.2"
msgid "‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā; "
msgstr "‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come, "

msgctxt "mn106:4.3"
msgid "yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā; "
msgstr "sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come; "

#. VAR: rūpaṃ sabbaṃ rūpaṃ cattāri → yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ cattāri (bj, pts1)
msgctxt "mn106:4.4"
msgid "yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ sabbaṃ rūpaṃ cattāri ca mahābhūtāni, catunnañca mahābhūtānaṃ upādāyarūpan’ti. "
msgstr "whatever is form, all form is the four primary elements, or form derived from the four primary elements.’ "

msgctxt "mn106:4.5"
msgid "Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati. "
msgstr "Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension. "

msgctxt "mn106:4.6"
msgid "Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā. "
msgstr "Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom. "

msgctxt "mn106:4.7"
msgid "Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ. "
msgstr "When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable. "

msgctxt "mn106:4.8"
msgid "Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati. "
msgstr "This is said to be the second way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: nya5, pts-vp-pli2.263, sc4
msgctxt "mn106:5.1"
msgid "Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati: "
msgstr "Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects: "

msgctxt "mn106:5.2"
msgid "‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā; "
msgstr "‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come, "

msgctxt "mn106:5.3"
msgid "yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā; "
msgstr "sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come, "

# NOTE: here rupa is neither “matter “nor” sights” but the meditation visions, i.e. what the later tradition called “nimittas”.
msgctxt "mn106:5.4"
msgid "ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpā, ye ca samparāyikā rūpā; "
msgstr "visions in this life and in lives to come, "

msgctxt "mn106:5.5"
msgid "yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā rūpasaññā—"
msgstr "perceptions of visions in this life and in lives to come; "

msgctxt "mn106:5.6"
msgid "ubhayametaṃ aniccaṃ. "
msgstr "all of these are impermanent. "

msgctxt "mn106:5.7"
msgid "Yadaniccaṃ taṃ nālaṃ abhinandituṃ, nālaṃ abhivadituṃ, nālaṃ ajjhositun’ti. "
msgstr "And what’s impermanent is not worth approving, welcoming, or clinging to.’ "

msgctxt "mn106:5.8"
msgid "Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati. "
msgstr "Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension. "

msgctxt "mn106:5.9"
msgid "Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā. "
msgstr "Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom. "

msgctxt "mn106:5.10"
msgid "Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ. "
msgstr "When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable. "

msgctxt "mn106:5.11"
msgid "Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati. "
msgstr "This is said to be the third way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
